et Relations Between Cuba and the US] from the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160115205405/https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/handle/10822/552494 Dean Peter Krogh Foreign Affairs Digital Archives]\n*[http://www.wilsoncenter.org/index.cfm?topic_id=1409&fuseaction=va2.browse&sort=Collection Cold War International History Project: Primary Document Collection on US-Cuban Relations]\n*BBC: [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3182150.stm Timeline: US-Cuba Relations]\n*[http://www.historyofcuba.com/history/teller.htm Complete text of the Teller amendment]\n*[http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/mod/1901platt.html Complete text of the Platt amendment]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060804210322/http://www.cafc.gov/ U.S. Commission for Assistance to a Free Cuba]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070224104729/http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/us-cuba/diaz-lanz-hearing.htm US Judiciary Hearings of Communist Threats to America Through the Caribbean]\n*[http://www.democracynow.org/2014/10/2/secret_history_of_us_cuba_ties Secret History of U.S.-Cuba Ties Reveals Henry Kissinger Plan to Bomb Havana for Fighting Apartheid]. ''[[Democracy Now!]]'' 2 October 2014.\n\n{{Cuba-United States relations}}\n{{Foreign relations of Cuba}}\n{{Foreign relations of the United States |expanded=Bilateral}}\n{{Portal bar|Cuba|United States|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuba - United States Relations}}\n[[Category:Cuba\u2013United States relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Cuba|United States]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Cuba]]\n", "name_user": "2601:183:847f:a013:b912:9c64:3c4c:afe6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuba%E2%80%93United_States_relations"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Berger (author)", "text_new": "{{short description|American journalist, author, and speaker|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Joseph Berger\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1945|1|17}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lysva]], Russia\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Journalist, author\n| language         = English\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = [[City College of New York]], 1966<br>[[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]]\n| genres            = Non-fiction \n| subjects          = History, social science, ethnic culture\n| notableworks     = ''Displaced Persons: Growing Up American After the Holocaust''\n| spouse           = Brenda\n| children         = 1\n| awards           = \n}}\n'''Joseph Berger''' (born January 17, 1945 in [[Lysva]], [[Soviet Union]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/berger.html|title=Ask A Reporter: Joseph Berger |date=1999|publisher=The New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021103045905/http://www.nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/berger.html |archive-date=November 3, 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is an American journalist, author, and speaker. He was a staff reporter and editor for ''[[The New York Times]]'' from 1984 to 2014 and has authored four books.\n\n==Early life and education==\nJoseph Berger was born in [[Lysva]], Russia,<ref name=ccny>{{cite web |url=https://www.ccnyalumni.org/alumni-relations/affiliates/communications-alumni/communications-hall-of-fame/316-berger-joseph-66|title=Joseph Berger, Class of 1966|publisher=[[City College of New York]] Alumni Association|year=2018|accessdate=October 21, 2018}}</ref> to Polish-born parents who had fled their hometowns to escape the Nazis.<ref name=los>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jul/10/news/mn-20455|title=Revealing the Struggles of Holocaust Survivors in U.S.|first=Josh|last=Getlin|date=July 10, 2001|accessdate=October 21, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Berger lived in several [[displaced persons camps in post-World War II Europe]] before immigrating to the United States in 1950 with his parents and younger brother.<ref name=times>{{cite web |url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/the-times-kosher-berger/|title=The Times' Kosher Berger|first=Ari L. |last=Goldman|date=August 7, 2012|accessdate=July 29, 2018|work=[[The Times of Israel]]}}</ref> A sister was born in the U.S. His book ''Displaced Persons: Growing Up American After the Holocaust'' describes his upbringing as a refugee child of Yiddish-speaking parents.<ref name=los/>\n\nBerger attended the [[Manhattan Day School]], an [[Orthodox Jewish|Orthodox]] yeshiva, followed by a year at [[Yeshiva University]], before enrolling at the [[Bronx High School of Science]].<ref name=jp>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/indepth/interviews-and-profiles/my-job-as-a-journalist-is-to-tell-the-story-an-interview-with-new-york-times-reporter-joseph-berger/2014/12/17/|title='My Job As A Journalist Is To Tell The Story': An Interview with New York Times Reporter Joseph Berger|first=Elliot|last=Resnick|date=December 17, 2014|accessdate=October 21, 2018|work=[[The Jewish Press]]}}</ref> After high school he attended the [[City College of New York]], graduating in 1966, and completed his M.A. in journalism at the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]].<ref name=ccny/>\n\n==Career==\nBerger was an English teacher from 1967 to 1971. He then became a feature writer for the ''[[New York Post]]'' from 1971 to 1978. He next worked as a reporter and religion writer for ''[[Newsday]]'' from 1978 to 1984.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Writers Directory|editor-first=Katherine H.|editor-last=Nemeh|edition=32nd|volume=1|location=Farmington Hills, MI|publisher=St. James Press|year=2014|p=250}}</ref>\n\nBerger joined the staff of ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 1984.<ref name=ccny/><ref name=times/> He served as chief religion correspondent from 1985 to 1987, and as national and local education correspondent from 1987 to 1993.<ref name=ccny/> He then served as deputy education editor and acting education editor, leading a 10-person staff.<ref name=ccny/> Berger wrote a column on education from 2006 to 2008.<ref name=ccny/> Articles that he wrote on New York's ethnic culture between 2004 and 2007 formed the basis for his book ''The World in a City: Traveling the Globe Through the Neighborhoods of the New New York''.<ref name=ccny/> He also served as a temporary assistant Metro editor and Times bureau chief in [[Jerusalem]]. He retired from the paper in December 2014.<ref name=jp/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nBerger was a three-time winner of the [[Religion Newswriters Association]]'s Supple Award during his stint at ''Newsday''.<ref name=ccny/> He received the 1993 Education Writers Association award \"for exposing biases in bilingual education\" and the 2011 Peter Kihss Award from the Society of the Silurians, for his reporting work and \"his interest in mentoring younger colleagues\".<ref name=ccny/><ref name=sholom/>\n\nBerger is a popular speaker on the subjects of immigration, education, New York City, the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], and Israel.<ref name=ccny/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBerger and his wife Brenda, a clinical psychologist and psychoanalyst, have one daughter.<ref name=sholom>{{cite web |url=https://www.sholom.net/2015/06/02/2015-confirmation-class/|title=Joseph Berger|first=Harriet|last=Plaxe|date=June 2, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2018|publisher=Temple Sholom of West Essex}}</ref> They reside in [[Westchester County]], where he is a member of a [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]] [[synagogue]].<ref name=times/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/youngscientistsa0000berg|url-access=registration|title=The Young Scientists: America's Future and the Winning of the Westinghouse|year=1994|publisher=Addison-Wesley|isbn=9780201632552}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/displacedpersons00berg|url-access=registration|title=Displaced Persons: Growing Up American After the Holocaust|publisher=Scribner|year=2001|isbn=9780684857572}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HclvDwAAQBAJ |title=The World in a City: Traveling the Globe Through the Neighborhoods of the New New York|year=2007|publisher=Ballantine Books|isbn=9780345487384}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jeVzAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=The Pious Ones: The World of Hasidim and Their Battles with America|year=2014|publisher=Harper Collins|isbn=9780062123350}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://forward.com/opinion/209174/the-hasidic-community-is-not-a-cult/ \"The Hasidic Community is not a Cult\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[The Forward]]'', November 18, 2014\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/travel/poland-jewish-heritage.html?_r=0 \"In Poland, Searching for Jewish Heritage\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 30, 2015\n*[https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/244797/the-smell-of-crayons-first-day-school-upper-west-side \"The Smell of Crayons\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]]'', September 12, 2017\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berger, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:The Bronx High School of Science alumn