ns, for his reporting work and \"his interest in mentoring younger colleagues\".<ref name=ccny/><ref name=sholom/>\n\nBerger is a popular speaker on the subjects of immigration, education, New York City, the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], and Israel.<ref name=ccny/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBerger and his wife Brenda, a clinical psychologist and psychoanalyst, have one daughter.<ref name=sholom>{{cite web |url=https://www.sholom.net/2015/06/02/2015-confirmation-class/|title=Joseph Berger|first=Harriet|last=Plaxe|date=June 2, 2015|accessdate=October 21, 2018|publisher=Temple Sholom of West Essex}}</ref> They reside in [[Westchester County]], where he is a member of a [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]] [[synagogue]].<ref name=times/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/youngscientistsa0000berg|url-access=registration|title=The Young Scientists: America's Future and the Winning of the Westinghouse|year=1994|publisher=Addison-Wesley|isbn=9780201632552}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/displacedpersons00berg|url-access=registration|title=Displaced Persons: Growing Up American After the Holocaust|publisher=Scribner|year=2001|isbn=9780684857572}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HclvDwAAQBAJ |title=The World in a City: Traveling the Globe Through the Neighborhoods of the New New York|year=2007|publisher=Ballantine Books|isbn=9780345487384}}\n\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jeVzAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=The Pious Ones: The World of Hasidim and Their Battles with America|year=2014|publisher=Harper Collins|isbn=9780062123350}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://forward.com/opinion/209174/the-hasidic-community-is-not-a-cult/ \"The Hasidic Community is not a Cult\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[The Forward]]'', November 18, 2014\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/travel/poland-jewish-heritage.html?_r=0 \"In Poland, Searching for Jewish Heritage\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 30, 2015\n*[https://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/244797/the-smell-of-crayons-first-day-school-upper-west-side \"The Smell of Crayons\" by Joseph Berger] ''[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]]'', September 12, 2017 \n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berger, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:The Bronx High School of Science alumni]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Lysva]]\n[[Category:Yeshiva University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II refugees]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Berger_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Clone Hero", "text_new": "{{short description|Indie rhythm video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| image = File:CloneHeroLogo.png\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]]\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| released = March 2017\n}}\n\n'''''Clone Hero''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Rhythm game|rhythm]] [[video game]] created by a small team of developers led by a user under the pseudonym of \"Srylain The 2nd\", first released circa March 2017. The game is a [[Clone (computing)|clone]] of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' franchise, and as such, features nearly identical gameplay. The main draw of the game is its ability to play community-made songs, which has resulted in a large [[Fandom|fan community]] around the game.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Clone Hero'', by design, features nearly identical gameplay to ''Guitar Hero''. Specifically, the game is most similar to later entries in the series such as ''[[Guitar Hero World Tour|World Tour]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock|Warriors of Rock]]''. Gameplay involves pressing colored buttons on a [[guitar]]-shaped controller to play along to songs, although in ''Clone Hero'' these inputs can be mapped to a keyboard or any other input device. Players must hold specific buttons that line up with colored notes that appear on the screen on a \"highway\"; when the notes hit the bottom of the highway, the player must strum to hit the notes in time with the music. There is also an \"open strum\" note, represented with a purple bar, which requires the player to strum without pressing any other buttons. In addition to normal notes, there are \"HOPO\"s (\"[[Hammer-on|Hammer-ons]]\" and \"[[Pull-off|Pull-offs]]\") and \"tap notes\", which both do not require the player to strum them to hit them, with the difference between the two being that a string of HOPOs must begin with a strum, and the player must re-strum if they miss a note. Unlike the ''Guitar Hero'' series, by default there is no penalty for missing notes, aside from breaking a combo, making it impossible to fail a song. The game also contains a mode which emulates the gameplay of ''[[Guitar Hero Live]]'', which is notably different from other games in the series.\n\n=== Community-made charts ===\n''Clone Hero'' has the ability to play community-made songs, called \"charts\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-01-meet-the-community-reviving-classic-guitar-hero-gameplay-in-their-own-clone|title=The spirit of Guitar Hero lives on in a bizarre community-made clone|last=Stubbs|first=Mike|date=2018-05-01|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/guitar-heroes-never-die-they-just-start-playing-clone-1828254899|title=Guitar Heroes never die, they just start playing Clone Hero|last=Neilan|first=Dan|date=August 10, 2018|website=AV Club|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> However, unlike games in the ''Guitar Hero'' series, these songs do not need to be original compositions, and can instead be any audio file a member of the community wishes to turn into a playable chart. This allows for any song to be made playable in the game, but also leads to many non-musical audio files being turned into charts,<ref name=\":1\" /> as well as the creation of many intentionally impossible charts.<ref name=\":0\" /> The freedom offered by the game's system has also spawned many charts that are created as brutal challenges to other players, far beyond the difficulty of anything in the standard ''Guitar Hero'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/meet-the-streamer-making-guitar-hero-cool-again-one-insanely-hard-song-at-a-time/|title=Meet the streamer making Guitar Hero cool again, one insanely hard song at a time|last=Winkie|first=Luke|date=2018-07-24|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/insane-guitar-hero-performance-goes-viral-after-jaw-dropping-speedrun-1312256|title=Insane Guitar Hero performance goes viral after jaw-dropping \"speedrun\"|last=Bennett|first=Connor|date=January 13, 2020|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> While ''Clone Hero'' includes the main 4 difficulty modes seen in ''Guitar Hero'', the vast majority of charts are designed for Expert mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Clone Hero'', along with ''Guitar Hero'', was listed as one of ''Gamepur''<nowiki/>'s top 10 best rhythm games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepur.com/features/10-best-rhythm-games|title=10 Best Rhythm Games|date=2020-01-22|website=Gamepur|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> ''Clone Hero'' has also made an appearance at [[Games Done Quick|Awesome Games Done Quick]] 2020.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2020/01/11/undertale-sans-wild-agdq-video/|title=Undertale's Sans Appears in Wild AGDQ Video|last=Deschamps|first=Marc|date=January 13, 2020|website=Comicbook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://clonehero.net/}}\n\n{{Guitar Hero series}}\n\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero]]\n[[Category:Guitar video games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Musician video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Software clones]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indie rhythm video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| image = File:CloneHeroLogo.png\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]]\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Clone Hero''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Rhythm game|rhythm]] [[video game]] created by a small team of developers led by a user under the pseudonym of \"Srylain The 2nd\". The game is a [[Clone (computing)|clone]] of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' franchise, and as such, features nearly identical gameplay. The main draw of the game is its ability to play community-made songs, which has resulted in a large [[Fandom|fan community]] around the game.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Clone Hero'', by design, features nearly identical gameplay to ''Guitar Hero''. Specifically, the game is most similar to later entries in the series such as ''[[Guitar Hero World Tour|World Tour]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock|Warriors of Rock]]''. Gameplay involves pressing colored buttons on a [[guitar]]-shaped controller to play along to songs, although in ''Clone Hero'' these inputs can be mapped to a keyboard or any other input device. Players must hold specific buttons that line up with colored notes that appear on the screen on a \"highway\"; when the notes hit the bottom of the highway, the player must strum to hit the notes in time with the music. There is also an \"open strum\" note, represented with a purple bar, which requires the player to strum without pressing any other buttons. In addition to normal notes, there are \"HOPO\"s (\"[[Hammer-on|Hammer-ons]]\" and \"[[Pull-off|Pull-offs]]\") and \"tap notes\", which both do not require the player to strum them to hit them, with the difference between the two being that a string of HOPOs must begin with a strum, and the player must re-strum if they miss a note. Unlike the ''Guitar Hero'' series, by default there is no penalty for missing notes, aside from breaking a combo, making it impossible to fail a song. The game also contains a mode which emulates the gameplay of ''[[Guitar Hero Live]]'', which is notably different from other games in the series.\n\n=== Community-made charts ===\n''Clone Hero'' has the ability to play community-made songs, called \"charts\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-01-meet-the-community-reviving-classic-guitar-hero-gameplay-in-their-own-clone|title=The spirit of Guitar Hero lives on in a bizarre community-made clone|last=Stubbs|first=Mike|date=2018-05-01|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/guitar-heroes-never-die-they-just-start-playing-clone-1828254899|title=Guitar Heroes never die, they just start playing Clone Hero|last=Neilan|first=Dan|date=August 10, 2018|website=AV Club|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> However, unlike games in the ''Guitar Hero'' series, these songs do not need to be original compositions, and can instead be any audio file a member of the community wishes to turn into a playable chart. This allows for any song to be made playable in the game, but also leads to many non-musical audio files being turned into charts,<ref name=\":1\" /> as well as the creation of many intentionally impossible charts.<ref name=\":0\" /> The freedom offered by the game's system has also spawned many charts that are created as brutal challenges to other players, far beyond the difficulty of anything in the standard ''Guitar Hero'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/meet-the-streamer-making-guitar-hero-cool-again-one-insanely-hard-song-at-a-time/|title=Meet the streamer making Guitar Hero cool again, one insanely hard song at a time|last=Winkie|first=Luke|date=2018-07-24|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/insane-guitar-hero-performance-goes-viral-after-jaw-dropping-speedrun-1312256|title=Insane Guitar Hero performance goes viral after jaw-dropping \"speedrun\"|last=Bennett|first=Connor|date=January 13, 2020|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> While ''Clone Hero'' includes the main 4 difficulty modes seen in ''Guitar Hero'', the vast majority of charts are designed for Expert mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Clone Hero'', along with ''Guitar Hero'', was listed as one of ''Gamepur''<nowiki/>'s top 10 best rhythm games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepur.com/features/10-best-rhythm-games|title=10 Best Rhythm Games|date=2020-01-22|website=Gamepur|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> ''Clone Hero'' has also made an appearance at [[Games Done Quick|Awesome Games Done Quick]] 2020.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2020/01/11/undertale-sans-wild-agdq-video/|title=Undertale's Sans Appears in Wild AGDQ Video|last=Deschamps|first=Marc|date=January 13, 2020|website=Comicbook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://clonehero.net/}}\n\n{{Guitar Hero series}}\n\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero]]\n[[Category:Guitar video games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Musician video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Software clones]]\n", "name_user": "AntiGravityMaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clone_Hero"}
{"title_page": "Messaging apps", "text_new": "{{other uses|Messaging application (disambiguation){{!}}Messaging application}}\n'''[[Message|Messaging]] apps''' (a.k.a. \"Social messaging\" or \"chat applications\") are apps and platforms that enable messaging, many of which started as adjunct to [[Social networking platform|social networking platforms]]. Many such apps have developed into broad platforms enabling status updates, [[chatbots]], [[payments]] and [[conversational commerce]] (e-commerce via chat).\n\nSome examples of popular messaging apps include [[WhatsApp]], [[Facebook Messenger|Facebook messenger]], China's [[WeChat]] and [[Tencent QQ|QQ Messenger]], [[Viber]], [[Line (application)|Line]], and [[Snapchat]]. [[Slack (software)|Slack]] focuses on messaging and file sharing for work teams. Some social networking services offer messaging services as a component of their overall platform, such as [[Facebook]]'s [[Facebook Messenger]], along with [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]]'s direct messaging functions.\n\nMessaging apps are the most widely used [[smartphone]] apps with in 2018 over 1.3 billion monthly users of WhatsApp and Facebook Messenger, 980 million [[monthly active users]] of WeChat and 843 million monthly active users of QQ Mobile.\n\n==Comparison to SMS and instant messaging==\nMessaging apps differ from the previous generation of [[instant messaging]] platforms, such as the defunct [[AIM (software)|AIM]], [[Yahoo! Messenger]], and [[Windows Live Messenger]], being primarily used via [[mobile apps]] on [[smartphones]], as opposed to personal [[computers]], although some messaging apps offer web-based versions or software for PC operating systems.\n\nDuring the 2010s, consumers moved from [[feature phone]]s to smartphones, and from paid services, such as traditional calling and SMS, to messaging apps which were available for free, or only incurred small data charges.<ref name=\"ondeviceresearch\">[https://ondeviceresearch.com/blog/messenger-wars-how-facebook-lost-its-lead Messenger Wars: How Facebook lost its lead] by OnDevice Research, a mobile market research company. Accessed on 21 January 2015.</ref> Easier group messaging was another advantage of smartphone messaging apps and also contributed to their adoption.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Church; de Oliveira|first=Karen; Rodrigo|date=2013|title=What's up with WhatsApp? Comparing Mobile Instant Messaging Behaviors with Traditional SMS|url=https://ic.unicamp.br/~oliveira/doc/MHCI2013_Whats-up-with-whatsapp.pdf|journal=Proceedings of Mobile HCI: 15th International Conference on Human-computer Interaction with Mobile Devices and Services|volume=|pages=352\u2013361|via=}}</ref> \n\nThe United States differs notably from most of the rest of the world in that SMS remains popular because it is usually included free in monthly phone bundles.<ref name=\"qz.com\">{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/487102/why-whatsapp-bombed-in-the-us-while-snapchat-and-kik-blew-up/|title=Why WhatsApp bombed in the US, while Snapchat and Kik blew up|first=Josh|last=Horwitz|publisher=}}</ref> Apple's iMessage is popular, and uses SMS for messages to non-Apple phones.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/27/technology/personaltech/weighing-unlimited-text-messages-against-apples-imessages.html|title=Weighing Unlimited Text Messages Against Apple's iMessages|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2016-02-26|last1=Biersdorfer|first1=J. D.}}</ref> While SMS volumes in some countries like Denmark, Spain and Singapore dropped up to two-thirds from 2011 to 2013, in the US SMS use only dropped by about one quarter.<ref name=\"qz.com\"/>\n\nBefore the introduction of messaging apps, smartphone users could only participate in single-person interactions via mobile voice calls or SMS. With the use of SMS and voice calls, group coordination is organized through singular calls/text messages to each individual group member. Although, one person can send the same text message to multiple group members, the group members can't see the responses of everyone else or even know who's in the group at all. Group members only have access to the messages they either send or receive, which hinders group coordination. With the introduction of messaging apps, users can form group chats, where all the members can see an entire thread of everyone's responses. Members can also respond directly to each other, rather than having to go through the member who started the group message, to relay the information. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ling |first1=Rich |last2=Lai |first2=Chih-Hui |title=Microcoordination 2.0: Social Coordination in the Age of Smartphones and Messaging Apps. |journal=Journal of Communication |date=October 6, 2016 |volume=66 |issue=5 |pages=834\u2013856 |doi=10.1111/jcom.12251 }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nMessaging apps each have some of the following features:\n\n* Chat\n** One-on-one chat\n** Group chat\n** Broadcast lists\n** [[Chatbots]] (including \"bot in group chats\")\n** \"Smart replies\" (suggested replies to incoming messages provided by Google's Reply platform )<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ausdroid.net/2018/02/22/googles-new-reply-app-makes-appearance-link-install-inside/|title=Google's new Reply app makes an appearance, link to install inside - Ausdroid|website=ausdroid.net|date=2018-02-22}}</ref>\n* Calls\n** Voice calls\n** Video calls\n* Audio alerts (on Line)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/05/07/economist-talks-advantages-line-over-whatsapp-mobile-messaging-push|title=The Economist talks on advantages of Line over Whatsapp for mobile messaging push|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[File sharing]]\n* Games\n* \"Mini Programs\" (e.g. WeChat Mini Program)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.wechat.com/cgi-bin/newreadtemplate?t=overseas_open/docs/mini-programs/development/brief-tutorial|title=Brief Tutorial - WeChat Open Platform|website=open.wechat.com}}</ref>\n* News discovery (e.g. Snapchat Discover)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/snap-tries-to-make-tv-and-magazines-coexist-on-snapchat-discover/|title=Does Snapchat Discover want to be TV or magazines? Maybe both|date=20 October 2017|publisher=[[Digiday]]}}</ref>\n* Payments or [[mobile wallet]], e.g. [[WeChat Pay]] which processes much of the Chinese [[mobile payment]] volume of US$5 trillion (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/08/china-is-living-the-future-of-mobile-pay-right-now.html|title=Cash is already pretty much dead in China as the country lives the future with mobile pay|first=Evelyn|last=Cheng|date=8 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Personal ([[cloud (computing)|cloud]]) storage<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/trending-stickers|title=Trending Stickers, Storage and More|website=Telegram}}</ref>\n* [[Push notifications]] \n* [[Status update]]s (WhatsApp Status,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://faq.whatsapp.com/en/android/26000031/|title=WhatsApp FAQ - Using Status|website=WhatsApp.com}}</ref> WeChat [[Moments (social networking)|Moments]])\n* [[Sticker (messaging)|Sticker]]s\n* [[Virtual assistant (artificial intelligence)|Virtual assistant]], e.g. [[Google Assistant]] in [[Google Allo]]\n\n== Conversational commerce ==\n[[Conversational commerce]] refers to [[e-commerce]] through the use of messaging, using either [[chatbots]] or human agents. In China, [[WeChat]] has shown strong growth; the messaging app also allows merchants to display goods in mobile Web pages and via social feeds. By 2013 e-commerce in China had overtaken that of the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/retail/our-insights/how-savvy-social-shoppers-are-transforming-chinese-e-commerce|title=How savvy, social shoppers are transforming Chinese e-commerce|website=McKinsey & Company}}</ref> In 2016, Facebook announced its [[Facebook Messenger]] [[chatbot]] platform, heralding the arrival of conversational commerce via the most widely used messaging app in the world outside of China. More than 34,000 businesses had opened shop on Messenger by August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/3211490/consumer-electronics/success-secrets-for-conversational-commerce.html|title=Success secrets for conversational commerce|first=Howard|last=Tiersky|publisher=}}</ref> In September 2017 [[WhatsApp]] announced the pilot of its new Enterprise solution \u2013 the first time large companies would be able to provide customer service to users via WhatsApp at scale.<ref name=\"whatsapp.com\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.whatsapp.com/10000633/Building-for-People-and-Now-Businesses|title=Building for People, and Now Businesses|website=WhatsApp.com}}</ref> Among the first companies announcing service on the enterprise platform were airlines [[KLM]] and [[Aerom\u00e9xico]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tecreview.itesm.mx/pronto-gracias-a-yalo-podras-chatear-aeromexico-via-whatsapp/|title=Ahora, gracias a Yalo, podr\u00e1s chatear con Aerom\u00e9xico v\u00eda Whatsapp - TecReview|first=Andrea|last=L\u00f3pez|date=30 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://expansion.mx/tecnologia/2017/10/30/yalo-la-tecnologia-mexicana-que-lleva-whatsapp-a-aeromexico|title=Yalo, la tecnolog\u00eda mexicana que lleva Whatsapp a Aerom\u00e9xico|publisher=}}</ref> Latin American [[online travel agency]] [[:es:Despegar.com|Despegar.com]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.com.mx/noticia/327572/0/despegar-comienza-a-brindar-servicios-por-whatsapp/|title=Despegar comienza a brindar servicios por WhatsApp|last=20Minutos|publisher=}}</ref> and online retailer [[Linio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.linio.com.mx/linio-primer-retailer-en-implementar-whatsapp-enterprise/|title=Linio primer retailer en implementar WhatsApp Enterprise - Linio Blog MX|date=26 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Comparison of instant messaging clients]]\n* [[Conversational commerce]]\n* [[Instant messaging]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{ cite web | url = http://blogs.rediff.com/thinko/2019/09/12/meet-the-new-age-creators-from-bharat-helos-platform-empowering-local-content-creators-2/\n | publisher = Rediff.com| title = Meet the new-age creators from 'Bharat' - Helo's platform empowering local content creators }}\n\n{{Mobile phones}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n\n[[Category:Social networking services]]\n[[Category:Instant messaging]]\n[[Category:Online chat]]\n[[Category:Text messaging]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Messaging application (disambiguation){{!}}Messaging application}}\n'''[[Message|Messaging]] apps''' (a.k.a. \"Social messaging\" or \"chat applications\") are apps and platforms that enable messaging, many of which started as adjunct to [[social networking platform]]s.<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/17/line-the-social-entertainment-platform/ Line: We\u2019re A Social Entertainment Platform, Not Just A Free Calls Messaging App] Accessed on 21 January 2015.</ref> Many such apps have developed into broad platforms enabling status updates, [[chatbots]], [[payments]] and [[conversational commerce]] (e-commerce via chat).\n\nSome examples of popular messaging apps include [[WhatsApp]], China's [[WeChat]] and [[Tencent QQ|QQ Messenger]], [[Viber]], [[Line (application)|Line]], [[Snapchat]], Korea's [[KakaoTalk]],<ref>[http://trends.e-strategyblog.com/2013/12/13/most-popular-social-messaging-apps/15939 Most Popular Social Messaging Apps, December 2013]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Accessed on 21 January 2015.</ref> [[Google Hangouts]], [[Blackberry Messenger]], [[Signal (software)|Signal]], [[Telegram (messaging service)|Telegram]], and Vietnam's [[Zalo]]. [[Slack (software)|Slack]] focuses on messaging and file sharing for work teams. Some social networking services offer messaging services as a component of their overall platform, such as [[Facebook]]'s [[Facebook Messenger]], along with [[Instagram]] and [[Twitter]]'s direct messaging functions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/twitter-becomes-a-messaging-app-by-getting-rid-of-140-character-limit-for-dms-2015-8|title=Twitter is a messaging app now that it's finally removed the 140 character limit on direct messages|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/09/08/twitter-now-acts-more-like-a-messaging-app-with-read-receipts-typing-indicators-web-link-previews/|title=Twitter now acts more like a messaging app with read receipts, typing indicators & web link previews|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMessaging apps are the most widely used [[smartphone]] apps with in 2018 over 1.3 billion monthly users of WhatsApp and Facebook Messenger, 980 million [[monthly active users]] of WeChat and 843 million monthly active users of QQ Mobile.<ref name=stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/258749/most-popular-global-mobile-messenger-apps/|title=Most popular messaging apps 2018 - Statista|website=Statista}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison to SMS and instant messaging==\nMessaging apps differ from the previous generation of [[instant messaging]] platforms, such as the defunct [[AIM (software)|AIM]], [[Yahoo! Messenger]], and [[Windows Live Messenger]], being primarily used via [[mobile apps]] on [[smartphones]], as opposed to personal [[computers]], although some messaging apps offer web-based versions or software for PC operating systems.\n\nDuring the 2010s, consumers moved from [[feature phone]]s to smartphones, and from paid services, such as traditional calling and SMS, to messaging apps which were available for free, or only incurred small data charges.<ref name=\"ondeviceresearch\">[https://ondeviceresearch.com/blog/messenger-wars-how-facebook-lost-its-lead Messenger Wars: How Facebook lost its lead] by OnDevice Research, a mobile market research company. Accessed on 21 January 2015.</ref> Easier group messaging was another advantage of smartphone messaging apps and also contributed to their adoption.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Church; de Oliveira|first=Karen; Rodrigo|date=2013|title=What's up with WhatsApp? Comparing Mobile Instant Messaging Behaviors with Traditional SMS|url=https://ic.unicamp.br/~oliveira/doc/MHCI2013_Whats-up-with-whatsapp.pdf|journal=Proceedings of Mobile HCI: 15th International Conference on Human-computer Interaction with Mobile Devices and Services|volume=|pages=352\u2013361|via=}}</ref> \n\nThe United States differs notably from most of the rest of the world in that SMS remains popular because it is usually included free in monthly phone bundles.<ref name=\"qz.com\">{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/487102/why-whatsapp-bombed-in-the-us-while-snapchat-and-kik-blew-up/|title=Why WhatsApp bombed in the US, while Snapchat and Kik blew up|first=Josh|last=Horwitz|publisher=}}</ref> Apple's iMessage is popular, and uses SMS for messages to non-Apple phones.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/27/technology/personaltech/weighing-unlimited-text-messages-against-apples-imessages.html|title=Weighing Unlimited Text Messages Against Apple's iMessages|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2016-02-26|last1=Biersdorfer|first1=J. D.}}</ref> While SMS volumes in some countries like Denmark, Spain and Singapore dropped up to two-thirds from 2011 to 2013, in the US SMS use only dropped by about one quarter.<ref name=\"qz.com\"/>\n\nBefore the introduction of messaging apps, smartphone users could only participate in single-person interactions via mobile voice calls or SMS. With the use of SMS and voice calls, group coordination is organized through singular calls/text messages to each individual group member. Although, one person can send the same text message to multiple group members, the group members can't see the responses of everyone else or even know who's in the group at all. Group members only have access to the messages they either send or receive, which hinders group coordination. With the introduction of messaging apps, users can form group chats, where all the members can see an entire thread of everyone's responses. Members can also respond directly to each other, rather than having to go through the member who started the group message, to relay the information. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ling |first1=Rich |last2=Lai |first2=Chih-Hui |title=Microcoordination 2.0: Social Coordination in the Age of Smartphones and Messaging Apps. |journal=Journal of Communication |date=October 6, 2016 |volume=66 |issue=5 |pages=834\u2013856 |doi=10.1111/jcom.12251 }}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nMessaging apps each have some of the following features:\n\n* Chat\n** One-on-one chat\n** Group chat\n** Broadcast lists\n** [[Chatbots]] (including \"bot in group chats\")\n** \"Smart replies\" (suggested replies to incoming messages provided by Google's Reply platform )<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ausdroid.net/2018/02/22/googles-new-reply-app-makes-appearance-link-install-inside/|title=Google's new Reply app makes an appearance, link to install inside - Ausdroid|website=ausdroid.net|date=2018-02-22}}</ref>\n* Calls\n** Voice calls\n** Video calls\n* Audio alerts (on Line)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/05/07/economist-talks-advantages-line-over-whatsapp-mobile-messaging-push|title=The Economist talks on advantages of Line over Whatsapp for mobile messaging push|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[File sharing]]\n* Games\n* \"Mini Programs\" (e.g. WeChat Mini Program)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://open.wechat.com/cgi-bin/newreadtemplate?t=overseas_open/docs/mini-programs/development/brief-tutorial|title=Brief Tutorial - WeChat Open Platform|website=open.wechat.com}}</ref>\n* News discovery (e.g. Snapchat Discover)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://digiday.com/media/snap-tries-to-make-tv-and-magazines-coexist-on-snapchat-discover/|title=Does Snapchat Discover want to be TV or magazines? Maybe both|date=20 October 2017|publisher=[[Digiday]]}}</ref>\n* Payments or [[mobile wallet]], e.g. [[WeChat Pay]] which processes much of the Chinese [[mobile payment]] volume of US$5 trillion (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/08/china-is-living-the-future-of-mobile-pay-right-now.html|title=Cash is already pretty much dead in China as the country lives the future with mobile pay|first=Evelyn|last=Cheng|date=8 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Personal ([[cloud (computing)|cloud]]) storage<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telegram.org/blog/trending-stickers|title=Trending Stickers, Storage and More|website=Telegram}}</ref>\n* [[Push notifications]] \n* [[Status update]]s (WhatsApp Status,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://faq.whatsapp.com/en/android/26000031/|title=WhatsApp FAQ - Using Status|website=WhatsApp.com}}</ref> WeChat [[Moments (social networking)|Moments]])\n* [[Sticker (messaging)|Sticker]]s\n* [[Virtual assistant (artificial intelligence)|Virtual assistant]], e.g. [[Google Assistant]] in [[Google Allo]]\n\n== Conversational commerce ==\n[[Conversational commerce]] refers to [[e-commerce]] through the use of messaging, using either [[chatbots]] or human agents. In China, [[WeChat]] has shown strong growth; the messaging app also allows merchants to display goods in mobile Web pages and via social feeds. By 2013 e-commerce in China had overtaken that of the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/retail/our-insights/how-savvy-social-shoppers-are-transforming-chinese-e-commerce|title=How savvy, social shoppers are transforming Chinese e-commerce|website=McKinsey & Company}}</ref> In 2016, Facebook announced its [[Facebook Messenger]] [[chatbot]] platform, heralding the arrival of conversational commerce via the most widely used messaging app in the world outside of China. More than 34,000 businesses had opened shop on Messenger by August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/3211490/consumer-electronics/success-secrets-for-conversational-commerce.html|title=Success secrets for conversational commerce|first=Howard|last=Tiersky|publisher=}}</ref> In September 2017 [[WhatsApp]] announced the pilot of its new Enterprise solution \u2013 the first time large companies would be able to provide customer service to users via WhatsApp at scale.<ref name=\"whatsapp.com\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.whatsapp.com/10000633/Building-for-People-and-Now-Businesses|title=Building for People, and Now Businesses|website=WhatsApp.com}}</ref> Among the first companies announcing service on the enterprise platform were airlines [[KLM]] and [[Aerom\u00e9xico]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tecreview.itesm.mx/pronto-gracias-a-yalo-podras-chatear-aeromexico-via-whatsapp/|title=Ahora, gracias a Yalo, podr\u00e1s chatear con Aerom\u00e9xico v\u00eda Whatsapp - TecReview|first=Andrea|last=L\u00f3pez|date=30 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://expansion.mx/tecnologia/2017/10/30/yalo-la-tecnologia-mexicana-que-lleva-whatsapp-a-aeromexico|title=Yalo, la tecnolog\u00eda mexicana que lleva Whatsapp a Aerom\u00e9xico|publisher=}}</ref> Latin American [[online travel agency]] [[:es:Despegar.com|Despegar.com]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.com.mx/noticia/327572/0/despegar-comienza-a-brindar-servicios-por-whatsapp/|title=Despegar comienza a brindar servicios por WhatsApp|last=20Minutos|publisher=}}</ref> and online retailer [[Linio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.linio.com.mx/linio-primer-retailer-en-implementar-whatsapp-enterprise/|title=Linio primer retailer en implementar WhatsApp Enterprise - Linio Blog MX|date=26 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Comparison of instant messaging clients]]\n* [[Conversational commerce]]\n* [[Instant messaging]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{ cite web | url = http://blogs.rediff.com/thinko/2019/09/12/meet-the-new-age-creators-from-bharat-helos-platform-empowering-local-content-creators-2/\n | publisher = Rediff.com| title = Meet the new-age creators from 'Bharat' - Helo's platform empowering local content creators }}\n\n{{Mobile phones}}\n{{Instant messaging}}